{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"8c8d21d7-5ffc-47de-9cae-a07073e78fe9","content":"Here are the **evaluation performance issues** in this project:\n\n---\n\n### 1. File I/O Property Function (High Impact)\n```xml\n<BuildNotes>$([System.IO.File]::ReadAllText('build-notes.txt'))</BuildNotes>\n```\nReading files via property functions happens during **evaluation**, blocking the MSBuild engine. This forces synchronous disk I/O before any build work begins.\n\n**Fix:** Move file reading to a target (execution phase) or use a custom task.\n\n---\n\n### 2. Overly Broad Glob Pattern (Medium Impact)\n```xml\n<AdditionalFiles Include=\"**\\*.*\" Exclude=\"**\\bin\\**;**\\obj\\**\" />\n```\n`**\\*.*` walks the **entire directory tree** during evaluation. As the repo grows (or if `node_modules`/`.git` folders exist), this becomes extremely expensive.\n\n**Fix:** Add large directories to `DefaultItemExcludes` or narrow the glob to specific extensions/subdirectories.\n\n---\n\n### 3. Deep Import Chain (Low-Medium Impact)\n```\nEvalHeavy.csproj → level1.props → level2.props → level3.props\n```\nA 3-level deep chain of imports. Currently small, but this pattern scales poorly—each additional level adds evaluation overhead and makes preprocessing/debugging harder.\n\n**Fix:** Flatten where possible, or consolidate into a single `.props` file.\n\n---\n\n### Summary\n\n| Issue | Severity | Phase |\n|-------|----------|-------|\n| `File::ReadAllText` in property | 🔴 High | Evaluation |\n| `**\\*.*` recursive glob | 🟡 Medium | Evaluation |\n| 3-level nested imports | 🟢 Low | Evaluation |\n\nThe most impactful fix is removing the `System.IO.File::ReadAllText` call from the property evaluation.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"87cf21ad-f93d-4638-91b5-e6b4a8c6d927","outputTokens":446,"requestId":"1C34:B22B0:C7A6C1:E83888:69F400E3"},"id":"0ddf8a85-033f-4e97-9706-83acf5ea9df0","timestamp":"2026-05-01T01:25:01.807Z","parentId":"c9e5e2d5-3ccb-4da4-9e45-946a98acaa05"}
